ewenglandhistoricalsociety.com/the-tragedy-of-hartfords-exploding-schoolhouse/","primary_url_label":"The tragedy of Hartford's exploding schoolhouse"},"cross_connections":[{"type":"event_overlap","related_id":"T01001","display_label":"Both buried in rubble of the 1766 schoolhouse explosion","link_text":"Col. Samuel Talcott"},{"type":"family_orbit","related_id":"H00533","display_label":"married his daughter Hannah Jones"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Levi Jones","first_name":"Levi","last_name":"Jones","married_names":[]},"residence":{"city":"Hartford","county":"Hartford","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM003"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"death","header":"Killed in 1766 Hartford schoolhouse explosion","body":"On 23 May 1766, gunpowder was being distributed to militia in the basement of the Hartford schoolhouse for the town's Stamp Act repeal celebration when boys on the floor above lit scattered powder and triggered an explosion that buried twenty-eight men in the rubble. He was among the six who died of their wounds, leaving Elizabeth Cook Jones with four children including seven-year-old Hannah, who later married into the Hooker line."},{"category":"legacy","header":"The exploding schoolhouse made national news","body":"Hartford's schoolhouse blast was carried by newspapers from Connecticut down to Virginia, a rare national story for 1766. Among the survivors was Colonel Samuel Talcott Jr., burned on the face and arms.","number":2},{"category":"family","header":"His young daughter married into the Hooker line","body":"Levi left a widow, Elizabeth Cook, and several children when he died. His daughter Hannah, then seven, grew up to marry William Hooker.","number":3}],"slug":"levi-jones-1717"},"X00050":{"id":"X00050","classification":{"include_i